---

# CONTRIBUTING

## Welcome to Corvus!

Thank you for considering contributing to the Corvus framework! We appreciate your interest in helping us build a better tool for Roblox developers. Whether you're reporting bugs, fixing typos, or adding new features, every contribution counts.

Before you start, please take a moment to review this document to understand our contribution process and guidelines.

---

## Getting Started

### Prerequisites

Make sure you have the following installed on your machine:

- **Roblox Studio**: Ensure you have the latest version of Roblox Studio installed.
- **Git**: Familiarize yourself with Git for version control.
- **Lua**: Basic knowledge of Lua/Luau programming is required.

### Setting Up Your Development Environment

1. **Fork the Repository**: Click the "Fork" button at the top right corner of the repository page.
2. **Clone the Repository**: Clone your forked repository to your local machine.

   ```bash
   git clone https://github.com/xsiuph/Corvus-Framework.git
   cd Corvus-Framework
   ```

3. **Set Up Your IDE**: Configure your favorite IDE or text editor to work with the project. Roblox Studio provides a built-in scripting environment, but you can also use external editors for advanced development.

---

## How to Contribute

### Reporting Issues

If you encounter a bug or have a feature request, please search the [issue tracker](https://github.com/xsiuph/Corvus-Framework/issues) to see if it has already been reported. If not, you can create a new issue following these steps:

1. Go to the [issues page](https://github.com/xsiuph/Corvus-Framework/issues).
2. Click the "New Issue" button.
3. Provide a clear and concise title and description of the issue.
4. Include any relevant details, such as error messages, screenshots, or steps to reproduce the issue.
5. Tag the issue appropriately (e.g., `bug`, `feature-request`, `documentation`).

### Submitting Pull Requests

1. **Fork the Repository**: If you haven't already, fork the repository.
2. **Create a New Branch**: Create a new branch for your changes.

   ```bash
   git checkout -b feature/my-new-feature
   ```

3. **Make Your Changes**: Implement your changes, ensuring they adhere to the coding standards outlined below.
4. **Write Tests**: Write unit tests for your changes to ensure they work as expected.
5. **Commit Your Changes**: Commit your changes with clear and descriptive commit messages.

   ```bash
   git add .
   git commit -m 'Add some AmazingFeature'
   ```

6. **Push to Your Fork**: Push your changes to your forked repository.

   ```bash
   git push origin feature/my-new-feature
   ```

7. **Open a Pull Request**: Go to the original repository and click "New Pull Request". Select your branch and compare it against the main branch. Provide a clear title and description for your pull request.

### Code of Conduct

Please follow the [Code of Conduct](CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md) when interacting with the project. We strive to maintain a welcoming and inclusive community.
---

## Guidelines

### Coding Standards

- **Naming Conventions**: Use camelCase for variable and function names, and PascalCase for class names [[10]].
- **Formatting**: Use consistent formatting throughout the codebase. Consider using a linter to enforce formatting rules.
- **Documentation**: Document your code thoroughly, especially for public APIs. Use comments to explain complex logic and provide examples where applicable.

### Testing

- **Integration Tests**: Ensure that your changes do not break existing functionality by running integration tests.

### Review Process

- **Initial Review**: Once your pull request is opened, it will be reviewed by maintainers.
- **Feedback**: Be open to feedback and willing to make changes based on reviewer comments.
- **Merge**: After addressing any feedback and passing all tests, your changes will be merged into the main branch.

---

## Becoming a Maintainer

If you're interested in becoming a maintainer, here's how you can contribute:

1. **Contribute Regularly**: Actively contribute to the project by submitting high-quality pull requests.
2. **Engage with the Community**: Participate in discussions on issues and pull requests, and help answer questions from other contributors.
3. **Propose Improvements**: Suggest process improvements, new tools, or documentation enhancements.
4. **Collaborate**: Work closely with other maintainers to ensure the project's success.

Once you've demonstrated a strong commitment to the project, you may be invited to become a maintainer.

---

## Support

For questions, issues, or suggestions, feel free to:

- Open an [Issue](https://github.com/xsiuph/Corvus-Framework/issues).
- Join our [Discord Community](https://discord.gg/your-discord-link) for real-time support and discussions.
- Follow us on [Twitter](https://twitter.com/CorvusFramework) for updates and announcements.

